Для тех, кто переезжает с Flask и Pyramid привычно группировать "ручки" в некоторый общий класс. Поэтому предлагаю рассмотреть вариант реализации подобного варианта в Muffin. 
Подробнее в доке https://pythonhosted.org/Flask-Classy.

Кратко хочется такого:
```
class MyCBVHandler(muffin.Handler):
    def get(self, request):
        return {'simple': 'rest', 'example': request.match_info.get('example')}

    def post(self, request):
        return [1, 2, 3]

    @app.register('/random')
    def random(self, request):
        return choice([1, 2, 3])

```

It would be really nice if the [Serialization](http://pint.readthedocs.org/en/0.6/serialization.html) page mentioned Python's json library. I would expect it to offer nothing except perhaps clarification on the best way to do this:

    class QtyJSONEncoder(JSONEncoder):
        def default(self, o):
            if isinstance(o, _Quantity):
                return str(o)
            return super(QtyEncoder, self).default(o)

Or just simply a recommended way for checking if a quantity is a Quantity object or not. Importing _Quantity seems naughty. As I see it, 90% of the time, the string representation is better than a split form, so I am using this in my Django app, rather than splitting to natives (which is what I assume is the recommended method).

As the title says, the loss gets negative quickly and the resulting network produces random results with a ton of false positive if I let the training run and let the loss go deep in the negative. 

I checked the output of 

```loss += truth->size()*options.loss_per_missed_target;
                for (auto&& x : *truth)
                {
                    if (!x.ignore)
                    {
                        point p = image_rect_to_feat_coord(input_tensor, x, sub);
                        loss -= out_data[p.y()*output_tensor.nc() + p.x()];

                        // compute gradient
                        g[p.y()*output_tensor.nc() + p.x()] = -scale;
                    }
                    else
                    {
                        // This box was ignored so shouldn't have been counted in the loss.
                        loss -= 1;
                    }
                }
```




Checking the loss value at line 579 of loss.h I can see the loss already gets negative at this point after a few thousands training steps, before even starting computing the truth hits, which means `loss -= out_data[p.y()*output_tensor.nc() + p.x()];` is probably subtracting more than it should. What does this operation represent exactly? I don't fully understand this and it would very useful to debug.

I have attached my bounding boxes here. Nothing special, a lot of boxes close to each other (so maybe something gets double counted in the process?) but very minimal overlap. 

[training_resized.txt](https://github.com/davisking/dlib/files/705778/training_resized.txt)

