```

Not really a bug, just a comment.

Since the tokenizer's maximum depth is stricter than that in the MediaWiki software, sometimes valid wikicode is wrongly parsed without emitting any warning notice. It would be good to have a status flag in order to be aware when that happens.

For example, if we parse 14 nested templates (valid code in MediaWiki), the outer one is given as text because MAX_DEPTH has been reached, but there is no communication to the user about this issue:

```python
txt = """{{a|
 {{b|
  {{c|
   {{d|
    {{e|
     {{f|
      {{g|
       {{h|
        {{i|
         {{j|
          {{k|
           {{l|
            {{m|
             {{n}}
            <!--m-->}}
           <!--l-->}}
          <!--k-->}}
         <!--j-->}}
        <!--i-->}}
       <!--h-->}}
      <!--g-->}}
     <!--f-->}}
    <!--e-->}}
   <!--d-->}}
  <!--c-->}}
 <!--b-->}}
<!--a-->}}"""

>>> tree = mwparserfromhell.parse(txt)
>>> [(type(x), str(x)[:10]) for x in tree.nodes]
[(mwparserfromhell.nodes.template.Template, '{{a|\n {{b|'),
 (mwparserfromhell.nodes.text.Text, '\n'),
 (mwparserfromhell.nodes.comment.Comment, '<!--a-->'),
 (mwparserfromhell.nodes.text.Text, '}}')]
```

I got some exception while use kafka-python

```python
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/kafka/selectors34.py", line 340, in select
    r, w, _ = self._select(self._readers, self._writers, [], timeout)
TypeError: select() takes at most 4 arguments (5 given)
```

```python
    if sys.platform == 'win32':
        def _select(self, r, w, _, timeout=None):
            r, w, x = select.select(r, w, w, timeout)
            return r, w + x, []
    else:
        _select = select.select
```

If the sys.platform is not 'win32', `self._select` will be `select.select`

and there will add one more argument `self`
I saw gevent use like this

```python
        if selectors.SelectSelector._select in (select.select, orig_select_select):
            def _select(self, *args, **kwargs):
                return select.select(*args, **kwargs)
            selectors.SelectSelector._select = _select
```

and there, the code can be this:

```python
    if sys.platform == 'win32':
        def _select(r, w, _, timeout=None):
            r, w, x = select.select(r, w, w, timeout)
            return r, w + x, []
    else:
        def _select(self, *args, **kwargs):
            return select.select(*args, **kwargs)
```

